Handle Missing Values

In[12]:
# Fill missing carrier names with 'Unknown'

df['Carrier_Name'] = df['Carrier_Name'].replace('','Unknown')

df['Carrier_Name'] = df['Carrier_Name'].fillna('Unknown',inplace=True)


# Fill missing port congestion levels with median

df['Port_Congestion_Level'] = df['Port_Congestion_Level'].fillna(df['Port_Congestion_Level'].median(),inplace=True)

Create Target Variable

In[18]:
# Convert Date Columns

df['Planned_ETA'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Planned_ETA'])

df['Actual_Arrival'] = pd.to_datetime(df['Actual_Arrival'])
In[19]:
# Create Target Variable

df['Delay_Days'] = (df['Actual_Arrival'] - df['Planned_ETA']).dt.days
In[20]:
df['Delayed'] = (df['Delay_Days'] > 0).astype(int)

Feature Engineering

Time-Based Features

In[26]:
df['ETA_Month'] = df['Planned_ETA'].dt.month

df['ETA_Weekday'] = df['Planned_ETA'].dt.weekday

df['Weekend'] = df['ETA_Weekday'].isin([5,6]).astype(int)

DistanceDistance per Month

In[27]:
df['Distance_per_Day'] = df['Distance_KM'] / (df['ETA_Month'] + 1)

Combined Congestion & Weather

In[28]:
df['Congestion_Weather'] = (df['Port_Congestion_Level'] * df['Weather_Index'])

Weather Severity

In[29]:
df['severe_weather'] = (df['Weather_Index'] >7).astype(int)

Model Tuning & Explainability

Random Forest Hyperparameter Tuning

In[47]:
def evaluate_model(y_true, y_pred, model_name="Model"):
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred))
    r2 = r2_score(y_true, y_pred)
    print(f" {model_name} Results")
    print(f"MAE: {mae:.4f}")
    print(f"RMSE: {rmse:.4f}")
    print(f"R2: {r2:.4f}")
    return mae, rmse, r2

# Define Random Forest Regressor
rf = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=42)

# Hyperparameter grid for RF
param_rf = {
    'n_estimators': [200, 400, 600, 800],
    'max_depth': [None, 10, 15, 20, 25],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4],
    'max_features': ['auto', 'sqrt', 'log2'],
    'bootstrap': [True, False]
}

# Randomized Search
rs_rf = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=rf,param_distributions=param_rf,n_iter=40,scoring='r2',cv=5,verbose=2,random_state=42,n_jobs=-1)

# Fit on training data
rs_rf.fit(x_train, y_train)

# Best RF model
best_rf = rs_rf.best_estimator_
print("Best Random Forest Parameters:", rs_rf.best_params_)

# Predict
y_pred_rf = best_rf.predict(x_test)

# Evaluate
evaluate_model(y_test, y_pred_rf, "Tuned Random Forest")

def evaluate_model(y_true, y_pred, model_name="Model"):
    mae = mean_absolute_error(y_true, y_pred)
    rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_true, y_pred))
    r2 = r2_score(y_true, y_pred)
    print(f" {model_name} Results")
    print(f"MAE: {mae:.4f}")
    print(f"RMSE: {rmse:.4f}")
    print(f"R2: {r2:.4f}")
    return mae, rmse, r2

results = pd.DataFrame(columns=['Model','MAE','RMSE','R2'])

models = {
    'Ridge Regression': y_pred_ridge,
    'Tuned Random Forest': y_pred_rf,
    'Tuned XGBoost': y_pred_xgb 
}

for name, pred in models.items():
    mae, rmse, r2 = evaluate_model(y_test, pred, name)
    results = pd.concat([results, pd.DataFrame({'Model':[name], 'MAE':[mae], 'RMSE':[rmse], 'R2':[r2]})], ignore_index=True)

shap.summary_plot(shap_values, x_test, feature_names=x.columns)

Conclusion & Key Takeaways

In this Delayed Freight Predictor project, I built an end-to-end machine learning solution to predict shipment delay days using a raw dataset of 5,000 historical freight records directly addressing the logistics challenge of unpredictable delays.

Main Achievements:

  • Achieved a strong test performance with MAE of ~2.12 days (average prediction error) and R of ~0.52 using Tuned XGBoost meaning the model explains over half of the delay patterns and predicts delays within roughly 2 days on average.
  • Demonstrated thorough data handling: cleaned missing values, standardized features, and created useful engineered variables (e.g., weekend flags, congestion-weather interaction).
  • Compared multiple algorithms (Linear/Ridge baseline + tree-based models like Random Forest, XGBoost, LightGBM) and showed clear improvement through hyperparameter tuning (e.g., XGBoost error reduced from 2.19 to 2.12 days).
  • Provided explainability with SHAP revealing Weather_Index, Port_Congestion_Level, and Hazardous Cargo as the top drivers of delays.

Business Impact:

  • With ~2.1-day average error, this model enables proactive actions: early customer alerts, buffer planning, rerouting risky shipments (e.g., high congestion + bad weather), and reduced detention/penalty costs (potentially 10k50k per affected container in real operations).
  • In a real freight forwarding setup, it could improve on-time delivery rates, customer satisfaction (NPS), and overall supply chain efficiency.

Limitations & Next Steps:

  • Limited to available features (no external data like holidays, carrier-specific history, or real-time events) future versions could incorporate these for even better accuracy.
  • Single train-test split; adding cross-validation would make metrics more robust.
  • Could explore ensemble methods (stacking Ridge + XGBoost) or deployment (Flask API / Streamlit dashboard) for production use.

Overall, this project demonstrates practical ML skills for real-world logistics problems: from raw messy data to an interpretable, tuned model with tangible business value. I'm excited to apply similar approaches to larger-scale supply chain challenges.
